text:
Hi. I'm founder and solo publisher of two curated newsletters, and I write a heck of a lot of content to fill and promote them.

One newsletter is _Driven,_ info and insights for time-strapped revenue leaders in B2B SaaS_._ 

The other is from the B2B Revenue Institute, another brand I founded. It's for revenue leaders (especially sales and marketing) in B2B companies (not SaaS).

Both focus mainly on enterprise sales, which a lot of people call "complex sales."

I'd like to make contact with anyone else who creates content for B2B SaaS, and especially anyone in SaaS companies that sell high-ticket software to big companies.

Our content needs are very different from those of people who sell "transactional" B2B SaaS offerings.

I'm in Atlanta.

Sorry to hear you've had that experience. I was often guilty of the same behavior when I was selling. I just wrote an article about this.

I often tell marketers that if you want job tenure and respect, get as close as you can to revenue, and stay there.

In my experience, salespeople, who often have more influence than marketers in B2B companies, have little respect for marketers who do branding. That's because marketers in branding don't make a direct or measurable contribution to revenue, and they don't work on a quota.

text:
In my opinion, a person who creates sales content has one overriding need: To learn about customers and prospects and how they make their buying decisions.

I'm not talking about something high-level and vague, like mapping the "customer journey."

Instead, I'm talking about understanding it in detail. You must know the stages in their decision process. You must know the questions they have in mind at each stage.

If you can help them answer the questions and concerns they have at each stage of their decision process, you can create sales content that's very helpful to both buyers and sales people. Because you can help advance the sale.
